BLUETONGUE - AUSTRALIA (02): (NORTHERN TERRITORY) BOVINE, SEROTYPE 12, OIE
**************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 16 Jul 2015
Source: OIE, WAHID weekly disease information 2015; 28(29) [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=18139


Bluetongue, Australia
--------------
Information received on [and dated] 16 Jul 2015 from Dr Mark Schipp, Chief Veterinary Officer, Ministry of Agriculture, Canberra, Australia

Summary
Report type: immediate notification (final report)
Date of start of the event: 5 Feb 2015
Date of confirmation of the event: 13 Jul 2015
Date event resolved: 9 May 2015
Reason for notification: New strain of a listed disease
Manifestation of disease: sub-clinical infection
Causal agent: Bluetongue virus
Serotype: 12
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks: Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: Beatrice Hill, Northern Territory
Date of start of the outbreak: 5 Feb 2015
Outbreak status: resolved (9 May 2015)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 24 / 4 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: Healthy sentinel herd with weekly blood samples collected for virus isolation and serology. No clinical disease detected. Seropositive only.

Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Cattle / 16.67 / 0 / 0 / 0
* Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction, and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive

Epidemiological comment: No disease has been detected. These findings occurred in the known bluetongue zone in northern Australia. Thirty years of regular structured surveillance have determined the extent of Australia's bluetongue zone and vectors (http://www.animalhealthaustralia.com.au/programs/disease-surveillance/national-arbovirus-monitoring-program/). Serotypes 1, 2, 3, 5, 7, 9, 15, 16, 20, 21 and 23 have previously been isolated in cattle in Northern Australia. It is believed that infected vectors are periodically blown to Australia on monsoonal winds. The detection of this new serotype is recognition of the effectiveness of the National Arbovirus Monitoring Program (NAMP) program. Identification of these isolates as bluetongue virus serotype 12 was established based on virus neutralisation assays and capillary sequencing of Seg-2 (VP2) and Seg-6 (VP5). Sequence analysis indicated all samples as belonging to Malaysia A genotype.

Control measures
Measures applied: vaccination prohibited; no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied; no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type:
Australian Animal Health Laboratory (OIE's Reference Laboratory)
Species / Test / Test date / Result
Cattle / reverse transcription-polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) / 26 Jun 2015 / Positive
Cattle / virus neutralization test (VNT) / 13 Jul 2015 / Positive
Cattle / virus sequencing / 6 Jul 2015 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is resolved. No more reports will be submitted.

The location of this outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.

